 employed to govern the child and young person within the context of the Irish juvenile justice system. This unique and original approach will appeal to legal scholars, criminologists and those with an interest in juvenile justice, history and social policy.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aJuvenile justice, Administration ofzIrelandxHistory. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Penology.2bisacsh  aIreland.  achildren.  agovernment.  agovernmentality.  ahistory.  ajuvenile justice.  aregulation.  areligious.  astate.  avoluntary.1 aSargent, Paul, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagez978311128363040uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978152611237840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526112378423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526112378/original  a978-3-11-128363-0  Manchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagec1986d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles